## What Is This?

ECR repositories default to `MUTABLE` tag mutability. This means any push to an existing tag silently overwrites it. `webapp:v1.0.0` deployed to production today can point to a completely different image tomorrow — no error, no alert, no audit log entry that says "this tag now points to a different digest."

This is tag tampering. An attacker with ECR push access overwrites a trusted version tag with a backdoored image. On the next ECS task restart, the new image is pulled silently.

Even without malicious intent, mutable tags break reproducibility. A rollback to `webapp:v1.0.0` no longer guarantees the same image that was originally deployed.

---

## Vulnerable Configuration

```hcl
# Default ECR — mutable tags
resource "aws_ecr_repository" "webapp" {
  name                 = "webapp"
  image_tag_mutability = "MUTABLE"  # default — dangerous
}
```

### Simulated Attack

```bash
# Step 1 — record current digest for v1.0.0
crane digest 123456789012.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/webapp:v1.0.0
# sha256:aabbccdd11223344...

# Step 2 — attacker overwrites the tag
docker build -t 123456789012.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/webapp:v1.0.0 \
    Dockerfile.backdoor .
docker push 123456789012.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/webapp:v1.0.0
# v1.0.0: digest: sha256:ff00ff00... (different digest — no error raised)

# Step 3 — digest changed silently
crane digest 123456789012.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/webapp:v1.0.0
# sha256:ff00ff00... (completely different image, same tag)
```

